<br>
Flayed Barbarian Skin Legs<br>
<br>
(from memory)<br>
<br>
60 AC, 100 HP, 10 STR, 10 DEX, 10 STA?<br>
<br>
Monk only<br>
<br>
Close anyway.  Now, if you view this as an item alone then I should imagine it would score very highly, the thought of level one monks running around in these would scare the hell out of warriors I should imagine (or any monk not close to 60).  Now consider what is required to obtain these - kill the Avatar of War, hope the drop.  Killing one of the most bad ass mobs in the game, a feat which few guilds can achieve, in order to aquire the item should really lower it's &quot;balance&quot; value quite siginficantly I would have thought, but how do you quantify that?<br>
<br>
Using just stats is like using any just one aspect of any other thing - it does not provide the true picture in order to make an assessment of balance.  A lot of the time you will see people argue this should be nerfed, or this should be beefed up, and they will quite often do so by comparing their class to one very small aspect of another as if comparing like with like.  It is a big trap to not step back and consider the environment within which this item/ability/skill exists.  The classes are not just a set of skills and abilities, they are a whole and should be considered as such.  Items are not just stats, they have a difficulty to attempt to aquire, in addition to the rarity of the item itself dropping when the mob is killed.<br>
<br>
This all makes it very hard to come up with a number.  It also makes it a daunting task to balance everything, I really don't envy Verant in that department.  <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bmonklybusiness43508.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=raphayl>Raphayl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Disciple</span><br>  Posts: 398<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/14/02 12:43:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=267.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Problem...</span><hr size=1> mouse:<br>
<br>
I see where you are coming from.  If you are considering placing a value on the ITEM, every one of your concerns are completely valid and understandable.  I would hate to try and determine a value for each item in the game, and I doubt it would even be feasible.  However, I was looking at it from a different point of view.<br>
<br>
Whatever the value of an ITEM, which must include the difficulty of obtaining it as you stated, the impact it has on the wearer would not change.  For example, you brought up the FBL.  Yes, in a system valuing the ITEM, if this item not only dropped form the AoW, but another item with identical stats for the same slot yet a different name dropped from some miniboss in Hate the value to the monk wearing it would be the same, no?  At least me, if an item gives me +100 hp it has no more or less impact on my character's ending ability whether it was a pain in the butt to acquire or relatively easy to acquire.  100hp is 100hp.<br>
<br>
I was referring to a sysem that places value on the impact of these sorts of things on the person that is currently wearing them, not the worth of the item itself to that person.<br>
<br>
If, for the pure sake of example, we use the item you posted:<br>
<br>
60 AC, 100 HP, 10 STR, 10 DEX, 10 STA<br>
<br>
... and we had a value sytem of, say:<br>
<br>
1hp = 1pt<br>
1ac = 3pt<br>
1str = 0.5pt(monk), 0.9pt(warrior)<br>
1dex = 0.1pt<br>
1sta = level/15(monk), level/10(warrior)<br>
<br>
then a 60 monk wearing this item would have their point value boosted by ((60 x 3)+(100 x 1)+(10 x .5)+(10 x .1)+(10 x 4))  = 326points<br>
<br>
Now a 60 warrior wearing this same item (at least one with the same stats... names don't make an item work better or worse) would get boosted by ((60 x 3)+(100 x 1)+(10 x .9)+(10 x .1)+(10 x 6))  = 350points<br>
<br>
So if we had these two fictional 60s together and were comparing them, and pretend they had absolutely no other skills, stats, equipment, whatever, then in this example they would we unbalanced in favor of the warrior.<br>
<br>
*****************************************<br>
On another note, I'm not so much pushing for a system that is designed for comparing equipped toons, so much as classes.  Of course, once two classes were compared using their levels on the class vs class scale, then you could also add in their equipment to get adjustments.  That way it would be easy to see why class X at level Y in gear Z could beat class A at level B in gear C at project N.<br>
<br>
Yes, some things would be difficult to &quot;value&quot;.  For example, what value does a Monk put on Instill Doubt?  What value does a Rogue put on it?  It's very possible that a rogue values it more than a monk of the same level.  A lot to consider.  But hey, looking at the flame fests going back and forth on these boards regarding balance, and their lengths.... it's not like we don't have the time on our hands, or that we don't care about balance.<br>
<br>
I appreciate your inputs =)  Part of what must be done is clarification of the system itself. <p>Raphayl <BR>
