</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ubumbleroot.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bumbleroot</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Young Grasshoppah</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/14/02 2:15:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=267.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Problem...</span><hr size=1> Quite simply it would be based on your ability to do damage and to save your group or self from taking damage over a set amount of time. The starting line would be totally naked and the finish line would be Y pts of damage per stat point and Y pts of damage saved per stat point.<br>
<br>
For example, you would need to determine how many times a level 60 cleric can cast CH with base stats (set a standard for each class based on the average starting stats of each class). There are mana calculators that can figure this out. If a cleric can cast 8 CHs with base stats at 10k per heal (current) then that is a total of 80,000 pts saved. My guess is that the duration that it takes this cleric to use up all of their CHs would be a good starting point to determine the set amount of time for the comparisons.<br>
I also think that  the damage output should be with a standard weapon that all classes can use with a easy ratio. A  9/18 weapon would be a good one to test all melee classes with since it breaks down to a .50 ratio.<br>
I'm sure there are already analysis done on how strength effects attack rating and how attack rating effects damage output. These should be applied to each class, and added in to a spreadsheet to determine the damage output per point.<br>
Stamina, Agility, Hit Points and resists simply are damage mitigation stats and ought to be considered when  measuring this end of the stick.<br>
The way to do this is to look at and place the most effective damage output and damage mitigation tools each class has. <br>
For example<br>
Warrior- Damage output- standard dual wield<br>
                Damage mitigation- No abilities, just additional stat bonuses.<br>
Cleric- Damage output- summoning hammer<br>
              Damage mitigation- Self Stats plus Complete heal<br>
Rogue- Damage output- Standard melee plus Backstab<br>
               Damage mitigation- Stats plus evasive<br>
Monk- Damage output-Standard melee plus kick<br>
             Damage mitigation-Stats plus mend Mend<br>
<br>
This doesn't take into effect the other abilites like Feining death, mezzing a mob etc. These are additional abilities and can in effect be an infinite amount of mitigation.<br>
<br>
I dont know the classes enough to list the types of base damage output and mitigation for each class. Can someone help me on this as well as some type of formulas to figure out the base damage and mitigation for each class on a similar skill and how it increases given additional stats.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bmonklybusiness43508.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=raphayl>Raphayl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Disciple</span><br>  Posts: 400<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/14/02 2:23:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=267.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Problem...</span><hr size=1> Zassk,<br>
<br>
You are absolutely correct.  Yet, I think that would be a natural part of the formula.  You can't just say a level 60 monk is better than a level 60 warrior.  Too many variables have been left out.  Still, time and again you see posts saying that Warriors are better than Monks, or vice versa.  Are you referring to an Iksar Monk, or Human Monk? Ogre Warrior or Gnome Warrior?  How many AA's does each have, and in what areas?  It's all of these things that people tend to forget to take into consideration when trying to &quot;measure up&quot; two characters.<br>
<br>
A chart where we had everything spelled out for everyone to see would point out weaker or stronger combinations, based on the weight of factors for each combination.  Notice in my very limited example above, STA had different values for Warriors and for Monks since they gain different amounts of hps from it.  I also gave Warriors more value for higher Str since they 1. gain more Attack per point of Str than Monks ( I believe Warriors get 1Attk per 1Str whereas Monks only gain 0.9), and 2. they get the added benefit of being able to carry around more weight due to it.  Is that worth another 0.4 per point of Str to Warriors?  That would be for them to say.  The chart would be something like this:<br>
<br>
Each 1 point of STR<br>
Class A = 1.5 Base  Racial Modifier X = x1.0  Y= x0.7  Z = x0.4<br>
Class B = 1.0 Base  Racial Modifier X = x1.0  Y= x0.9  Z = x0.1<br>
Class C = 0.7 Base  Racial Modifier X = x0.8  Y= x0.7  Z = x0.7<br>
<br>
But that would only be stats.  The important things are stuff like:(just examples)<br>
<br>
Monk FD Skill= 2000pts<br>
ShadowKnight FD Spell= 1700pts<br>
Necromancer FD Spell= 1400pts<br>
<br>
Monk ID = 200pts<br>
Rogue ID = 500pts<br>
<br>
Melee Regeneration = 3pts/regen pt<br>
Necromancer Regen = 8pts/regen pt<br>
Shaman Regen = 10pts/regen pt<br>
<br>
Monk Mend Skill = 500pt<br>
Paladin LoH ability = 20pt/level<br>
<br>
<br>
Far from complete or accurate, but you get the idea.  If this was used, a person could add up everything for their class, race, and level and come up with a value they could compare to any other combination to see who came out where for various situations.  I'd like to see just one chart taking into consideration the &quot;average sitation&quot;, but if that's too general it wouldn't be hard to tweek it into 3 tables of &quot;solo&quot;, &quot;exp groups&quot;, and &quot;raid&quot;.  Or something along those lines.<br>
<br>
Keep the feedback coming.  I respect and appreciate your insight. <p>Raphayl <BR>
